	<li>Argue in favour of IRL and long-form online conversation. Compare to clicktivism, i.e. "mouse clicks as proxies for political action and the self-selected, ideologically one-dimensional engagement fostered by social media"<a class="see-footnote" id="footnoteref2_zebqcb3" title="https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/books/2015/10/10/book-review-reclaiming-conversation-the-power-talk-digital-age-sherry-turkle/muXgP1rWCf5JIWNettgZDM/story.html" href="http://dandelion.liquidfridge.co.za/#footnote2_zebqcb3">2</a></li>
	<li>"Transforming civic knowledge into civic action is an essential part of democracy"<a class="see-footnote" id="footnoteref3_44ltwqa" title="https://civic.mit.edu/about" href="http://dandelion.liquidfridge.co.za/#footnote3_44ltwqa">3</a></li>
	<li>Consider an action component: "partner" with orgs in local community; clubs attend those events, e.g. data or wiki hackathon, beach cleanup, after-school reading; have a discussion before or after about the relevant issue; as a way to introduce the orgs, not necessarily commit full-time to any specific activism or volunteerism.</li>
	<li>"networked advocacy"</li>
</ul><h2>Mission</h2>

<ul><li>To create safe, public spaces for productive discussion about social, economic, political and ecological issues.</li>
	<li>To encourage civic engagement and prosocial actions in local communities.</li>
	<li>To share experiences, ideas and perspectives between communities.</li>
